This issue seems to be a Hydra and a new head has once more sprung up.  
Once again I will attempt lopping the head off.  I have read members&#39; QS 
whose choice of vowels seem peculiar to me in certain words as they are 
not the ones I would choose for that particular word.  Nevertheless, it 
has rarely caused me more than a moment&#39;s confusion in reading.  It is 
my firm conviction that the decrease in reading speed by letting people 
spell as they wish would be minimal.  That is a better solution than the 
burden that would be imposed on everyone by trying to mandate that words 
should be spelt according to someone&#39;s idea of what is &quot;correct&quot; or 
simplest for the largest number of speakers.  To me adopting spellings 
that require people to once again learn a sound scheme or look words up 
puts up firmly back into the TO trap we are trying to escape from.  I 
believe it stems from the unfortunate desire for control and 
regularity.  If we let people just spell any old way, who knows what 
they&#39;ll want to do next?

My feeling is that any attempt to enforce an arbitrarily determined 
&quot;standard&quot; no matter how well-intentioned, is doomed to failure.  
English-speaking people don&#39;t think that way.  We are not French -- we 
are not even German.  We have no language academy to enforce these 
things and no interest in having one.

I believe you are making a mountain out of a molehill here.  It is much 
simpler to simply let people spell words in the manner that seems 
natural to them.

In favor of limited anarchy, I remain.

Paige

